\f4\fs19\fsmilli9750 \cf9 \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 		\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec9 July 20, 2023
\f0\fs32 \cf2 \cb1 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa225\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs30 \cf9 \cb3 \strokec9 In July 1945, as J. Robert Oppenheimer and the other researchers of the Manhattan Project prepared to test their brand-new atomic bomb in a New Mexico desert, they knew relatively little about how that mega-weapon would behave.\cb1 \
\cb3 On July 16, when the plutonium-implosion device was set off atop a hundred-foot metal tower in a test code-named \'93{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nytimes.com/2021/08/03/science/trinity-site-atomic-fat-man.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf10 \ul \ulc10 \strokec10 Trinity}},\'94 the resultant blast was much stronger than anticipated. The irradiated mushroom cloud also went many times higher into the atmosphere than expected: some 50,000 to 70,000 feet. Where it would ultimately go was anyone\'92s guess.\cb1 \
\cb3 A\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://arxiv.org/pdf/2307.11040.pdf"}}{\fldrslt \cf10 \ul \ulc10 \strokec10 new study, released on Thursday}}\'a0ahead of submission to a scientific journal for peer review, shows that the cloud and its fallout went farther than anyone in the Manhattan Project had imagined in 1945. Using state-of-the-art modeling software and recently uncovered historical weather data, the study\'92s authors say that radioactive fallout from the Trinity test reached 46 states, Canada and Mexico within 10 days of detonation.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf9 \cb3 \'93It\'92s a huge finding and, at the same time, it shouldn\'92t surprise anyone,\'94 said the study\'92s lead author, S\'e9bastien Philippe, a researcher and scientist at Princeton University\'92s Program on Science and Global Security.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs32 \cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa225\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs30 \cf9 \cb3 \strokec9 The study also reanalyzed fallout from all 93 aboveground U.S. atomic tests in Nevada and created a map depicting composite deposition of radioactive material across the contiguous U.S. (The team also hopes to study U.S. tests over the Pacific Ocean in the future).\cb1 \
\cb3 How much of Trinity\'92s fallout still remain at original deposition sites across the country is difficult to calculate, said Susan Alzner, an author of the study and the co-founder of shift7, an organization that coordinated the study\'92s research. The study documents deposition as it originally hit the ground in 1945.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf9 \cb3 \'93It\'92s a frozen-in-time image,\'94 she said.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

