\f1\fs22\fsmilli11250 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4 Estimated radionuclide deposition density for the first 10 days after detonation of the Trinity test on July 16, 1945, at 5:29 a.m. local time.
\fs32 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf4 \cb3 Credit\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs19\fsmilli9750 \cf4 \cb3 Credit...\cb1 \
\cb3 S\'e9bastien Philippe, Susan Alzner, Gilbert P. Compo, Mason Grimshaw, Megan Smith
\fs32 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa225\partightenfactor0

\fs30 \cf9 \cb3 \strokec9 The findings could be cited by advocates aiming to increase the number of people eligible for compensation by the federal government for potential exposure to radiation from atmospheric nuclear explosions.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf9 \cb3 The drift of the Trinity cloud was monitored by Manhattan Project physicists and doctors, but they underestimated its reach.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs32 \cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa225\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs30 \cf9 \cb3 \strokec9 \'93They were aware that there were radioactive hazards, but they were thinking about acute risk in the areas around the immediate detonation site,\'94 Alex Wellerstein, a nuclear historian at the Stevens Institute of Technology in New Jersey, said. They had little understanding, he said, about how the radioactive materials could embed in ecosystems, near and far. \'93They were not really thinking about effects of low doses on large populations, which is exactly what the fallout problem is.\'94\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs32 \cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa225\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs30 \cf9 \cb3 \strokec9 At the time, Dr. Stafford L. Warren, a Manhattan Project physician specializing in nuclear medicine, reported to Lt. Gen. Leslie Groves, leader of the Manhattan Project, that the Trinity cloud \'93remained towering over the northeast corner of the site for several hours.\'94 Soon, he added, \'93various levels were seen to move in different directions.\'94 Dr. Warren assured General Groves that an assessment of the fallout\'92s reach could be undertaken later on horseback.\cb1 \
\cb3 In the decades that followed, a lack of crucial data has bedeviled assessments and attempted studies of the Trinity test\'92s fallout. The U.S. had no national monitoring stations in place in 1945 to track the fallout, Dr. Philippe said. Plus, essential historical weather and atmospheric data was available only from 1948 onward. Remodeling fallout from tests in Nevada \'97 starting in 1951 \'97 was easier, but Trinity remained frustratingly difficult to reanalyze.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf9 \cb3 \'93The data sets for the Nevada tests and the available data that we could possibly find for Trinity were not comparable,\'94 Ms. Alzner said. \'93You couldn\'92t put them on the same map. We decided to keep pushing.\'94\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs32 \cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
